Prologue
"I implore you!" Queen Eirwen pleaded, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. In the eyes of the Ice King, a girl meant weakness. After all, he had only fathered sons up to this point.
"You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That's its punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat her name out as if it were venom. He always did.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, in the South a kingdom full of fantastical powers. But the North showed its greed and it came to an endless war between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They proposed sending their only princess as queen to the North, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South into a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg of you, my king, do with me as you will, imprison me, banish me or kill me, but spare my child," Queen Eirwen pleaded, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with disgust. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times and given him his sons.
"I suppose the child can stay in the palace," he said, which was noted by the queen with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King instructed the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's vacant rooms. Then, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the gallows, where all the citizens of the city could witness her execution.
While the guards escorted her to the gallows, a loud uproar erupted among the citizens, as they realized their only and beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others shouted and attacked the guards, while others wondered why this was happening, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Executioner. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even a criminal. It was the most horrific thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The citizens of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the Executioner lit the wooden stake ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Give not up, Queen Eirwen." This was the end of the reign of Queen Eirwen.
Deathly silence in the palace
Only a knocking sound could be heard from the room located far to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by would often wonder what was in the room, and they were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors were circulating among the maids that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting to be released.
Her guess could not have been more off the mark, thought Ivory, and headed towards the south wing as the servants scurried by, whispering to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors also concerned Ivory, as Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory in front of the intricately decorated door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if – unlike the last attempt – she would actually be granted access. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against her shoulder, but apologized immediately once she realized who she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from within, presumably to indicate that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory had entered without asking.
From within, Ivory heard a knock. That likely meant a "yes". The cold and the noise made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a noise from a supposedly empty room, although Ivory had been going in there for several years.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that awaited Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Papers were scattered everywhere, books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot), and the room looked like a blizzard had blown through.
The girl lay rolled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and read in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"What notebook is that?" asked Ivory and sat down beside Kari on the bed.
